      {
        "content": "Social media's global connectivity benefits do not justify the pervasive privacy violations users experience. Even if platforms promote positive interactions, they often do so by leveraging detailed user data, infringing on privacy rights. The claim that social media empowers individuals fails to account for how companies exploit personal data, often invisibly, for profit. The lack of transparent data practices poses significant risks, including identity theft and surveillance, overshadowing potential benefits. Without strict regulation ensuring data protection and user control, any claimed connectivity advantages are overshadowed by the fundamental breach of user privacy rights.",
        "additional_kwargs": {
          "refusal": null
